Boris Boehlen wrote:

&gt; Hello,
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt; When I start the TestRunner provided by Ant first the method &quot;runTest&quot;
&gt;&gt;&gt; is executed (which is OK). But then the other methods are executed in an
&gt;&gt;&gt; arbritrary order (I suppose). How can I change this behaviour?
&gt;&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt;&gt; Simply rename your test methods so they don&#39;t start with *test* word, this
&gt;&gt; will prevent them to be executed by TestRunner.
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; This is a possible solution I found too. IMHO this is not very useful in 
&gt; my case, because I still like to know which tests succeeded and which didn&#39;t.
&gt; Unfortunately this does only work if you have written &quot;testXXX&quot; methods because
&gt; JUnit invokes these methods independantly. 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt;&gt; Dependent actions should be written within one test case. There was
&gt;&gt; a discussion on this mailing list few weeks ago (look for the thread [junit]
&gt;&gt; Order of Tests).
&gt; 
&gt; I found these discussions and do not agree. In my application area the 
&gt; result is that I have several mini test case which depend heavily on
&gt; each other. The glue between them would be a number of test cases which 
&gt; must themselves be used in larger test suites (can I nest test suites,
&gt; btw?).
&gt; 
&gt; Regards
&gt; 	Boris Boehlen

It&#39;s possible to explicitly define the test method order in the suite() 
method, as in...

     public static Test suite() {
         TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();
         suite.addTest(new ExampleTestCase(&quot;testA&quot;));
         suite.addTest(new ExampleTestCase(&quot;testB&quot;));
         suite.addTest(new ExampleTestCase(&quot;testC&quot;));
         return suite;
     }

